```javascript
function sumofDigits(n) {
  if (n < 10) {
    return n;
  } else {
    return (n % 10) + sumofDigits(Math.floor(n/10));
  }
}

// Example usage:
console.log(sumofDigits(12345)); // Output: 15
console.log(sumofDigits(987654321)); // Output: 45
```

The `sumofDigits()` function takes a number `n` as input and recursively sums up the individual digits using the modulo operator and integer division. The `if` condition checks if the number is less than 10, meaning there's only one digit left to sum up, and returns it as is. Otherwise, the function sums up the rightmost digit of the number (`n % 10`) and returns it added to the sum of the remaining digits obtained by calling itself with `Math.floor(n/10)`.

